Local Inner Class in Java

A local inner class is a class defined inside a method.

👉 It is used only within that method and cannot be accessed from outside.

Basic Example
class Outer {
    void method() {
        class Local {
            void print() {
                System.out.println("Hello from local inner class");
            }
        }

        Local obj = new Local();
        obj.print();
    }
}
Key Features
defined inside a method
accessible only within that method
cannot be used outside
does NOT use static
has limited scope
Accessing Variables

Local inner class can access:

outer class fields
local variables (only if they are final or effectively final)
Example
class Outer {
    void method() {
        int x = 10; // effectively final

        class Local {
            void print() {
                System.out.println(x);
            }
        }

        new Local().print();
    }
}

👉 If you change x, it will cause an error

Why use Local Inner Class?

Use it when:

class is needed only inside one method
want to keep code clean and scoped
logic is small and specific
When NOT to use
if class is reused in multiple places
if logic is large or complex
Local Inner vs Inner Class
Feature	Local Inner Class	Inner Class
Defined in	method	class
Scope	limited to method	whole class
Access outside	❌	✅
Summary
local inner class = class inside a method
used only within that method
can access effectively final variables
helps keep code clean and limited in scope
